No, apparently not. The creature just growled and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Luckily, Thassalin was agile enough despite his size and dodged, but Nyssi let out a scream as she almost lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
“HOW CAN WE KILL IT?” Nyssi screamed.
“TARGET THEIR HEADS!”
“THAT WILL BE DIFFICULT!”
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, closer to the mountain he called home. The dark creature followed, but became slightly panicked when it was hit by a firebeam from behind. It hadn't realized it was no longer alone. It became even more panicked when Thassalin slowed down and then swung his tail at its head, knocking it off course.
Growling and snarling, it flew upwards and spat into the air. Everything suddenly became dark, as if the monster was sucking the light from the sky into itself and replacing it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he could see nothing anymore, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping against the tree branches before finally crashing into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and shot directly at him, dragging the black cloud with it.
“Kayel!” Tenuk screamed as he slid out of the cloud and began to circle, looking for Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. “What are we supposed to do now? Kayel… Kayel, where are you?”
Down below, Nyssi slowly got to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her unusual, supernatural healing powers were already starting to work. Unfortunately, this did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that hadn't collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made an effort to get close to Thassalin, but she could hardly see two meters in front of her. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in those shadows, something was screaming and screeching.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed to the ground next to Nyssi, knocking her off balance. But she noticed that the tail was only wildly swinging and not deliberately trying to hit her. The beast, or what little Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and swiped at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, struck the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a rifle shot echoed through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground, and remained motionless. The darkness surrounding them lifted, and they saw what had happened: Kayel stood on the beast, heavily panting as he held his rifle.
“That was probably… The craziest shadow jump I've ever made… Thanto kat'olon…”, Kayel gasped for air. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy swirled around his body. But while he was still speaking, the color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow color.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He rarely used them, because most people found them eerie and quite intimidating. But Nyssi hadn't known that Kayel could use these powers in any type of darkness. And the way Kayel behaved, he was obviously quite surprised too.
“Are you okay?” Nyssi burst out.
“Yes, I'm fine. I killed something, I'll be okay again soon.” Kayel examined his work, as Tenuk flew down, landed beside him, and resumed his normal "spast" form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see what it was. Its skin was as black as coal and slimy, but the slime stuck to its body. It had four wings and four extremities, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could even ask what in the world they were facing, something screamed and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it didn't get to them because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to stumble and come to a stop in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi didn't want to take any risks. She grabbed her shotgun and fired without thinking, hitting the creature's head and killing it on the spot.
“Whoa...”, Retvik muttered from the driver's seat before awkwardly turning off the engine and getting out of the truck. “Uh, that wasn't exactly intentional. Are you all okay?”
“You missed the whole action,” Tenuk snapped. “Where were you?”
“You just left me standing there. I came as fast as I could…”, Retvik sighed. “Can I ask, what are those terrible creatures?”
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had recovered. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not too severely injured.
“YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WERE LEAVING HERE AS CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS.”
“You mean the terrifying god-monster creature that we… helped to kill?” Tenuk stuttered.
“YES. THAT'S IT. MAYBE THERE ARE MORE. BUT I COULDN'T THINK CLEARLY. I DON'T HAVE A GUN. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, RIGHT?” Thassalin limped over to Kayel and patted him on the head. “Thanks, little one. You remind me of my old friend Arkadin. Just not so murderous and not so capable of killing entire universes.”
“Uh… thanks… I think…”, Kayel shrugged. “So, are we done here then?”
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the now definitely dead beasts. Then she pulled out her favorite weapon, the decorated Death God dagger, and began to saw off one of the beast's horns. Next, she tackled the second one. But just as Nyssi finished, the beasts suddenly caught fire and transformed into a heap of ash in an instant. The same thing happened to the horns she had cut off.
“So, that's both practical and impractical at the same time…”, Nyssi sighed. “But at least I have the photos, hopefully.”
